   130	glance, the electron energy. But then it occurred to me that, because my
   131	coupling systems surely would not work perfectly, giving an absolutely
   132	pure running wave in the accelerator tube, the electrons in a real LINAC
   133	would, after all, emit some high-frequency radiation.
   134	
   135	The "useful" accelerating wave, carrying perhaps 10 megw of power,
   136	will be accompanied, inevitably, by a small reflected wave of perhaps 1
   137	megw.
   138	
   139	Let us think of it as a plane wave, of a microwave frequency
   140	$\omega_0/2\pi = 3$ GHz, Poynting vector
   141	$S_0 = P_0/A = 2 \times 10^5 \text{ watts/cm}^2$, traveling in the (-z)
   142	direction.
   143	[Of course, the reflected wave in a LINAC is not a plane wave, the
   144	transverse field $E_r \sim J_1(kr)$ vanishing on the axis where one
   145	tries to keep the electron beam. But by the Poynting theorem, a given
   146	reflected power $P_0$ requires a certain average $\langle E_r^2 \rangle$ over the disc
   147	apertures A. Therefore, while our plane wave treatment does not describe
   148	the situation that LINAC operators now try to achieve, it does describe,
   149	within unimportant numerical factors.]
